    "summary": "\"The metaphysical\" is better — \"object\" conflicts with category theory and reifies what the author deconstructs",
    "content": "**\"The metaphysical\" is better as the default. Use \"metaphysical construct\" when needed for clarity. Avoid \"metaphysical object.\"**\n\nThree reasons:\n\n1. **\"Object\" is wrong in category theory context.** In the author's framework, a 形而上 is defined as a universal property (a morphism/association in E that is a terminal or initial object in some subcategory). Calling it a \"metaphysical object\" would confuse it with categorical objects (the things in Obj_E). The author's 形而上 is structurally a *property* of a subcategory, not an object in the base category --- even though, due to the tower structure, it also exists as an object at a higher meta-order. \"Metaphysical object\" invites exactly the wrong reading: a thing sitting in E, rather than a structural feature of E.\n\n2. **\"The metaphysical\" preserves the adjectival/processual character.** The author repeatedly insists that 形而上 is constructed *upon* phenomena --- it is an understanding, an interpretation, an abstraction. \"The metaphysical\" (substantive adjective) preserves this quality: it names a *mode* or *character* of understanding, not a discrete entity. \"Metaphysical object\" reifies it into exactly the kind of standalone entity the author's post-metaphysical framework is trying to move past.\n\n3. **Context-dependent alternatives.** In passages where the grammar requires a countable noun --- \"a 形而上\" or \"several 形而上\" --- use \"metaphysical construct\" or \"a metaphysical\" (the latter following the pattern of \"a universal\" in mathematics). In the formal definition passage, \"a metaphysical\" works naturally: \"a metaphysical *m* is an association in E such that *m* is a universal property in some subcategory of E.\"\n\nSummary: \"the metaphysical\" (general/uncountable) and \"a metaphysical\" or \"metaphysical construct\" (specific/countable). Never \"metaphysical object.\""
  }
